1590","Taplow, Buckinghamshire, England":"Taplow, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt. 1590–":"circa 1590–Overleden","1587–Male":"1587–Overleden","1610–Male":"1610–Overleden","1590–Female":"1590–Overleden","1610":"1610","1587":"1587","1590":"1590","Abt. 1590":"circa 1590","Taplow, Buckinghamshire, England":"Taplow, Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Kensington, Middlesex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt. 1590–":"about 1590–Deceased","1587–Male":"1587–Deceased","1610–Male":"1610–Deceased","1590–Female":"1590–Deceased","1610":"1610","1587":"1587","1590":"1590","Abt. 1590":"about 1590","Taplow, Buckinghamshire, England":"Taplow, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fox","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from a word denoting the animal (Middle English, Old English <i>fox</i>), widely used to denote a sly or cunning individual. It was also used for someone with red hair. In England this surname absorbed some early examples of surnames derived from the ancient Germanic personal names mentioned at   Faulks   and   Foulks  .","Irish: part translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an tSionnaigh</b> ‘son of the fox’ (see   Tinney  ).","Irish: also adopted for <b>Ó Catharnaigh</b>, see   Kearney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Foxe","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Fox  .","Altered form of English   Fox  ."]},{"name":"Foxx","meanings":["Variant of   Fox  ."]},{"name":"Faulks","meanings":["English: from the Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fauque</i>, <i>Fauques</i>, <i>Fau(l)ques</i> (oblique case <i>Fau(l)que</i>), originally an ancient Germanic byname <i>Falco</i>, meaning ‘falcon’."]},{"name":"Foxman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Charna, Isadore, Shmuel.","Jewish (American): variant of   Fox  ."]},{"name":"Fuchs","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Hans, Kurt, Gerhard, Fritz, Mathias, Matthias, Armin, Ulrich, Erwin, Helmut.","German and Jewish: from Middle High German <i>vuhs</i>, German <i>Fuchs</i> ‘fox’, a nickname for a sly or cunning person, or for someone with red hair. This surname is also found in France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Poland, Czechia, and Slovenia, often as a translation into German of corresponding Slavic nicknames or surnames. Compare   Fox   4,   Fuks  , and   Futch  ."]},{"name":"Kearney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Seamus, Caitlin, Declan, Dermot, Donovan, Eamonn, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Catharnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Catharnach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘warlike’. Alternatively, it may be from <b>Ó Cearnaigh</b> or <b>Mac Cearnaigh</b> (from <i>cearnach</i> ‘victorious’) or from <b>Ó Ceithearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceithearnach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘foot soldier’.","History: Most present-day bearers of this name are descended from Tadhg Ó Catharnaigh, killed in battle in 1084. He was nicknamed <i>An Sionnach</i> ‘the Fox’, and for this reason the Irish surname was sometimes Anglicized as   Fox  . Denis Kearney, born in Oakmont, Ireland, in 1847, was a US labor movement leader."]}]},{"name":"Emily","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a medieval form of the Latin name <i>Aemilia</i>, the feminine version of the old Roman family name <i>Aemilius</i> (probably from <i>aemulus</i> ‘rival’). It was not common in the Middle Ages, but was revived in the 19th century and is extremely popular throughout the English-speaking world today. Its best-known 19th‐century bearer was probably the novelist and poet  Emily Brontë  (  1818–48 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Emilie","meanings":["From Latin <i>Aemilia</i>.  See  Emily ."]}]},{"name":"Josephine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French <i>Joséphine</i>, a feminine equivalent of   Joseph   formed with the diminutive suffix <i>-ine</i>. It is now widely used in the English-speaking world. Notable bearers have included the British social reformer  Josephine Butler  (  1828–1906 ) and the American-born French dancer and singer  Josephine Baker  (  1906–75 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Emily Josephine Fox was born about 1590, in Taplow, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Henry Fox."},"et":{"Abt. 1590–":"umbes 1590–Surnud","1587–Male":"1587–Surnud","1610–Male":"1610–Surnud","1590–Female":"1590–Surnud","1610":"1610","1587":"1587","1590":"1590","Abt. 1590":"umbes 1590","Taplow, Buckinghamshire, England":"Taplow, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Kensington, Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt. 1590–":"noin 1590–Kuollut","1587–Male":"1587–Kuollut","1610–Male":"1610–Kuollut","1590–Female":"1590–Kuollut","1610":"1610","1587":"1587","1590":"1590","Abt. 1590":"noin 1590","Taplow, Buckinghamshire, England":"Taplow, Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Kensington, Middlesex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt. 1590–":"environ 1590–Décédée","1587–Male":"1587–Décédé","1610–Male":"1610–Décédé","1590–Female":"1590–Décédée","1610":"1610","1587":"1587","1590":"1590","Abt. 1590":"environ 1590","Taplow, Buckinghamshire, England":"Taplow, Buckinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Kensington, Middlesex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Emily Josephine Fox est née environ 1590, à Taplow, Buckinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-U